   "quote-source" : "The Economist, <em><a href=\"http://www.economist.com/node/21564413\">History: As you were</a></em>",
   "quote-text" : "<p>Jane Austen&rsquo;s &ldquo;Pride and Prejudice&rdquo; is a story about love. It is also about inheritance and income gaps. The heroine, Elizabeth Bennet, comes from a well-off family, the second of five daughters. But her financial future is dark because, in the absence of sons, her father&rsquo;s estate will pass to a cousin. Elizabeth&rsquo;s suitor, the brooding Mr Darcy, is fabulously wealthy. To her mother&rsquo;s horror, Elizabeth at first rebuffs him.</p>\n\n<p>All ends happily when Elizabeth decides that Darcy is ravishing after all. But her motherâs reaction is a rational response to the realities of income distribution and social mobility in Austen&rsquo;s time. In an entertaining analysis of inequality, &ldquo;The Haves and the Have Nots&rdquo;, Branko Milanovic works out that by marrying Mr Darcy, Elizabeth would increase her income 100-fold. Without him, she would have the same income as a merchant seaman. With him she would be catapulted into the top 0.1%.</p>",
